{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"140"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582435"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:42:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:42:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"140"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/140"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.69,0.12,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/140"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"203"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a six-month history of episodes of shortness of breath, chest tightness, and choking sensations. During these episodes, she fears she is dying. On two occasions, she has woken in the night with these symptoms. The episodes peak within 10 minutes and terminate spontaneously. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe visited the Emergency Department two weeks ago during one such episode, where an ECG showed a sinus tachycardia of 106/min. She has been unable to attend her regular desk job for the past two weeks. She denies any precipitating event and is otherwise well. On examination, she appears anxious but has vital signs within normal limits. Blood and urine tests have all been normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first line management option for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Propranolol","Cognitive behavioural therapy","Fluoxetine","Diazepam","Imipramine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman is presenting with symptoms consistent with a diagnosis of panic disorder. She has been experiencing recurrent, unexpected panic attacks (including nocturnal panic attacks) and has engaged in maladaptive behaviour in response (not attending work). \u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for panic disorder. It helps patients identify and challenge their catastrophic thoughts and provides strategies to manage anxiety symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E, an SSRI, can be effective in the management of panic disorder. However, as a first-line option, it should be offered together with graded exposure to anxiety triggers, not as a standalone treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImipramine\u003C/strong\u003E is a tricyclic antidepressant. While tricyclics have shown efficacy in the management of panic disorder, they are not recommended as first-line treatment due to poor tolerability and side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E, a beta-blocker, has been proposed for use in social anxiety disorder, particularly the performance subtype, to decrease heart rate and tremor. However, this is no longer recommended, and there is no established role for beta-blockers in panic disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is a benzodiazepine. While benzodiazepines can be effective for short-term symptom relief in panic disorder, they are not recommended as first-line treatment due to the risk of dependence, difficulty with cessation, and high relapse rates upon discontinuation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cognitive behavioural therapy should be the first approach in the management of a patient with panic disorder.","Panic disorder is characterized by recurrent, unexpected panic attacks and maladaptive behaviors in response to these attacks.","SSRIs can be effective in managing panic disorder but should be offered alongside graded exposure to anxiety triggers."],"references":["Andrews G, Bell C, Boyce P et al. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for the treatment of panic disorder, social anxiety disorder and generalised anxiety disorder.\u00a0ANZCP. 2018; 52(12):1109-1172."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39245"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"140"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39245","links":{"self":"https: